Starting Monday Research Source Map
Version: 2026-05-20
Scope: Verified and/or peer-reviewed sources only

Scoring
- Relevance: 1 to 5, where 5 means directly useful to Starting Monday's core product and positioning.
- Legitimacy confidence: 1 to 5, where 5 means the source is clearly peer-reviewed or published by a highly reliable institutional publisher and is easy to verify.

Selection note
- I excluded unverified blogs, opinion pieces, and non-institutional commentary.
- I also excluded books where I could not quickly verify a stable publisher page.
- The list below prioritizes peer-reviewed journal articles, meta-analyses, systematic reviews, and verified institutional publications.

Core sources for Starting Monday

1) Richard R. Kilburg (1996). "Toward a conceptual understanding and definition of executive coaching." Consulting Psychology Journal: Practice and Research.
Link: https://doi.org/10.1037/1061-4087.48.2.134
Type: Foundational peer-reviewed article
Relevance: 5/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: Baseline definition of executive coaching; useful for positioning Starting Monday as coaching infrastructure rather than generic productivity software.

2) B.-K. Joo (2005). "Executive coaching: A conceptual framework from an integrative review of practice and research." Human Resource Development Review.
Link: https://doi.org/10.1177/1534484305280866
Type: Peer-reviewed review article
Relevance: 5/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: Strong framework for how coaching works and where leverage points exist.

3) Katherine Ely, Lisa A. Boyce, Johnathan K. Nelson, Stephen J. Zaccaro, Gina Hernez-Broome, and Wynne Whyman (2010). "Evaluating leadership coaching: A review and integrated framework." The Leadership Quarterly.
Link: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.leaqua.2010.06.003
Type: Peer-reviewed review/framework
Relevance: 5/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: One of the best sources for understanding coaching outcomes, mechanisms, and evaluation.

4) Tim Theeboom, Bianca Beersma, and Annelies E. M. van Vianen (2014). "Does coaching work? A meta-analysis on the effects of coaching on individual level outcomes in an organizational context." The Journal of Positive Psychology.
Link: https://doi.org/10.1080/17439760.2013.837499
Type: Peer-reviewed meta-analysis
Relevance: 5/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: Strong quantitative support that coaching can improve outcomes.

5) Rebecca J. Jones, Stephen A. Woods, and Yves R. F. Guillaume (2016). "The effectiveness of workplace coaching: A meta-analysis of learning and performance outcomes from coaching." Journal of Occupational and Organizational Psychology.
Link: https://doi.org/10.1111/joop.12119
Type: Peer-reviewed meta-analysis
Relevance: 5/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: Directly supports the argument that coaching affects learning and performance.

6) Simmy Grover and Adrian Furnham (2016). "Coaching as a developmental intervention in organisations: A systematic review of its effectiveness and the mechanisms underlying it." PLoS ONE.
Link: https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0159137
Type: Peer-reviewed systematic review
Relevance: 4/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: Good synthesis of effectiveness and underlying mechanisms; useful for explaining how the product should work.

7) Amalia Athanasopoulou and Sue Dopson (2018). "A systematic review of executive coaching outcomes: Is it the journey or the destination that matters the most?" The Leadership Quarterly.
Link: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.leaqua.2017.11.004
Type: Peer-reviewed systematic review
Relevance: 5/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: Specifically about executive coaching, making it one of the most relevant sources on the list.

8) Gil Bozer and Rebecca J. Jones (2018). "Understanding the factors that determine workplace coaching effectiveness: A systematic literature review." European Journal of Work and Organizational Psychology.
Link: https://doi.org/10.1080/1359432X.2018.1446946
Type: Peer-reviewed systematic review
Relevance: 4/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: Helps identify coach, coachee, and context factors that drive success.

9) Nicolau A., Candel O. S., Constantin T., and Kleingeld A. (2023). "The effects of executive coaching on behaviors, attitudes, and personal characteristics: a meta-analysis of randomized control trial studies." Frontiers in Psychology.
Link: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37333584/
Type: Peer-reviewed meta-analysis
Relevance: 5/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: Strong, newer evidence base for executive coaching effects.

10) Cannon-Bowers J. A., Bowers C. A., Carlson C. E., Doherty S. L., Evans J., and Hall J. (2023). "Workplace coaching: a meta-analysis and recommendations for advancing the science of coaching." Frontiers in Psychology.
Link: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37881215/
Type: Peer-reviewed meta-analysis / field synthesis
Relevance: 4/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: Strong current synthesis and a useful source for method and evidence framing.

11) James W. Smither, Manuel London, Raymond Flautt, Yvette Vargas, and Ivy Kucine (2003). "Can working with an executive coach improve multisource feedback ratings over time? A quasi-experimental field study." Personnel Psychology.
Link: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1744-6570.2003.tb00142.x
Type: Peer-reviewed quasi-experimental field study
Relevance: 5/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: Direct field evidence that executive coaching can improve performance-related measures.

Behavior change, preparation, and follow-through

12) Edwin A. Locke and Gary P. Latham (2002). "Building a practically useful theory of goal setting and task motivation: A 35-year odyssey." American Psychologist.
Link: https://doi.org/10.1037/0003-066X.57.9.705
Type: Peer-reviewed theory review
Relevance: 5/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: Core source for accountability, goal clarity, and deliberate preparation.

13) Peter M. Gollwitzer (1999). "Implementation intentions: Strong effects of simple plans." American Psychologist.
Link: https://doi.org/10.1037/0003-066X.54.7.493
Type: Peer-reviewed article
Relevance: 5/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: Best single source for turning intentions into action.

14) Peter M. Gollwitzer and Paschal Sheeran (2006). "Implementation intentions and goal achievement: A meta-analysis of effects and processes." Advances in Experimental Social Psychology.
Link: https://doi.org/10.1016/S0065-2601(06)38002-1
Type: Peer-reviewed meta-analysis chapter
Relevance: 5/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: Strong evidence that concrete if-then plans improve follow-through.

15) Susan J. Ashford and J. Stewart Black (1996). "Proactivity during organizational entry: The role of desire for control." Journal of Applied Psychology.
Link: https://doi.org/10.1037/0021-9010.81.2.199
Type: Peer-reviewed field article
Relevance: 4/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: Useful for onboarding and executive transition behavior.

16) Talya N. Bauer, Todd Bodner, Berrin Erdogan, Donald M. Truxillo, and Jennifer S. Tucker (2007). "Newcomer adjustment during organizational socialization: A meta-analytic review of antecedents, outcomes, and methods." Journal of Applied Psychology.
Link: https://doi.org/10.1037/0021-9010.92.3.707
Type: Peer-reviewed meta-analysis
Relevance: 5/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: One of the strongest sources for role-entry and onboarding design.

17) Serge Perrot, Talya N. Bauer, David Abonneau, Eric Campoy, Berrin Erdogan, and Robert C. Liden (2014). "Organizational Socialization Tactics and Newcomer Adjustment." Group & Organization Management.
Link: https://doi.org/10.1177/1059601114535469
Type: Peer-reviewed journal article
Relevance: 4/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: Helpful for designing structured onboarding and transition support.

18) Samantha A. Conroy and Anne M. O'Leary-Kelly (2014). "Letting Go and Moving On: Work-Related Identity Loss and Recovery." Academy of Management Review.
Link: https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2011.0396
Type: Peer-reviewed review article
Relevance: 4/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: Excellent for the identity side of executive transition.

Decision quality and weak-signal detection

19) Daniel Kahneman and Gary Klein (2009). "Conditions for intuitive expertise: A failure to disagree." American Psychologist.
Link: https://doi.org/10.1037/a0016755
Type: Peer-reviewed article
Relevance: 4/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: Useful for framing when executives should trust judgment and when they should slow down and verify.

20) H. Igor Ansoff (1975). "Managing Strategic Surprise by Response to Weak Signals." California Management Review.
Link: https://doi.org/10.2307/41164635
Type: Peer-reviewed management article
Relevance: 5/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: Classic weak-signal framework; directly maps to Starting Monday's signal-tracking value proposition.

21) Ross W. E., Huang K. H., and Jones G. H. (2014). "Executive onboarding: ensuring the success of the newly hired department chair." Academic Medicine.
Link: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24667516/
Type: Peer-reviewed review / applied article
Relevance: 4/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: Good applied source on onboarding structures, especially for high-stakes leadership transitions.

22) Rathmell W. K., Brown N. J., and Kilburg R. R. (2019). "Transformation to Academic Leadership: The Role of Mentorship and Executive Coaching." Consulting Psychology Journal.
Link: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31787830/
Type: Peer-reviewed article
Relevance: 4/5
Legitimacy confidence: 5/5
Why it matters: Useful for coaching-based onboarding and leadership acceleration.

Best sources to cite first for Starting Monday

If you only use eight pieces, use these:
1. Kilburg 1996
2. Ely et al. 2010
3. Theeboom et al. 2014
4. Jones et al. 2016
5. Athanasopoulou and Dopson 2018
6. Smither et al. 2003
7. Gollwitzer 1999
8. Bauer et al. 2007

What these sources collectively support
- Executive coaching works, but effects are mechanism-dependent.
- Follow-through improves when goals are broken into concrete if-then plans.
- Transition and onboarding outcomes improve when people get structured support.
- Weak signals matter in high-stakes decision environments.
- The most credible Starting Monday story is not "more coaching"; it is "better between-session execution infrastructure."

Potential next step
- Convert this source map into a claim-to-citation matrix for product pages, articles, investor materials, and the HBR submission.
